:alert:  **GM SN30** :w_: 
We have just bumped the min reg cost to `0.5 𝞃` . We want to combat bad actors from registering and providing bad outputs while collecting emissions during the immunity period.
We may bring this back down in the future but are putting this in place while we work with existing miners and validators on a better incentive mechanism

one reason emissions can be going down is there may be a bad actor cheating the stress test, making the rest of the "good" miners drop in relative score.
last update we patched a small vulnerability for exactly this. 

we have also added a "penalty" to miners that don't respond accurately to user requests, or if user requests are skipped
a new update should be out shortly that decreases the initial stress test to just 4 from the current 8

does the initial stress test affect future incentive for miner? 
Example: i first use a 4090 then switch to 8x4090 is not as high as first 4x4090 then 8x4090
the stress test is an ongoing process, if your setup upgrades over time you will perform better on the stress test giving you a higher bonus factor

Our thought process here is to have more performant miners. So you dont have to split your GPU power across multiple hotkeys
i.e. say all gpus are equal for this example
If miner A has 8 GPUs and miner B has 1 GPU, miner A should have 8x the incentive of miner B, so long as both produce adequate results are following the rules

This gets a bit messy with different hardware but logic is the same, if miner C can produce N times more output than miner D, miner A should have N times higher incentive
this allows the network to have higher total throughput

import random
import time

def generate_random_prompt(nouns, adjectives, verbs):

    noun = random.choice(nouns)
    verb = random.choice(verbs)
    randomness = base64.b64encode(str(random.randint(1,100) * time.monotonic_ns()).encode("ascii")).decode("ascii")
    return f"{adjective} {noun} {verb} {randomness}"
